<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubuppy.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Buppy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#333333>(9/14/02 7:23:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=341.topic&index=37>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Opinions in the end game: Vex Thal</span><hr size=1> Very nice original post and I'm glad to see yet another mage extolling our virtue in high-end Luclin. But I have a few things to say.<br>
<br>
Tell a mage on a Naggy raid how awesome the class is. Tell all the &lt;56 mages how needed they are on raids.<br>
<br>
Being great in high-end Luclin doesn't make us great in the rest of the world. Being required for raid guilds based on one spell may be 'balancing' and does allow us an opportunity we would not likely have otherwise, but it's still a tenuous link. One little change could eliminate the need for TRods, and therefore mages.<br>
<br>
I am not someone to normally be negative, or even one to post at all for that matter, and I DO NOT think mages are 'underpowered' or 'useless' or anything else the more vocal and negative crowd posts about. I am very happy being a mage and I know how powerful we are and can be. I have tried nearly every class, and none has held my attention very long. I do however know the game (not necessarily the class) needs some improvement to make it more fun. It has since the day it was released and it will until the day it dies. Verant knows it too, and the reason they do is because of the people who 'whine'.<br>
<br>
The ONLY reason mages have been improved in the higher end is because of the people complaining about the imbalances that are/were in game at the time. All the VT capable mages now crowing about how powerful they feel in Luclin are the same ones who were 'whining' about how impotent they felt in Velious. Now that you are beyond that content you forget what you went through. Just like the level 60 hybrids complained when the exp penalty was removed. Just because you lived through it doesn't mean everyone else should, or that it is good for the game.<br>
<br>
The good thing is Verant doesn't listen to you. They are a very good team, and have created what I would strongly argue is the best video game ever made. One of the primary reasons it's as good as it is, is because Verant listens to the complaints, and they do evaluate the game based on those complaints, and when they find problems they do their best to correct them. Sometimes it takes a while, and sometimes they don't agree with the complaints, but they do listen and they do react.<br>
<br>
Recently on this board I have seen a LOT more whining ABOUT whining than I have about the class. You really need to understand that feedback is INVARIABLY negative. The so-called 'positive' posts here are mostly just negative posts aimed at someone elses complaints, rather than true praises of our class power. Positive reinforcement only truely comes from a lack of complaints.<br>
<br>
The complaining is often over the top, I agree. But this boards and others like it are a great source of feedback for Verant. We should keep the complaints flowing, no matter how ridiculous, and trust Verant's judgement. Very few people in game actually frequent message boards, a lot less give much credence to what they read, and fewer still to boards not related directly to their class. Mage complaints here of being weak have NO impact on the opinions of &gt;99% of the rest of the EQ population. If mages (or any other class for that matter) have problems stemming from public opinion of them, you can bet that opinion is in large measure based on fact. Rangers were a common joke for their vulnerability, quite simply because they were weak defensively. Verant gave them defensive upgrades. That's how things work.<br>
<br>
Every class in the game should feel important in every stage of a game we PAY to play. Telling people complaining about something they don't like that they should be happy with what they have or play another class is like telling someone at Red Lobster complaining about rancid sea bass that they should be glad it wasn't worse, or they should've ordered the shrimp scampi. We pay for the service Verant provides, and that makes them obligated to provide us with a service we feel is satisfactory, or risk losing our business. Losing any business will hurt the game as a whole, so Verant has a vested interest in keeping as many people happy as they can, and so does everyone who wants to keep playing. Many of those people are not raiding anything much less VT, and many will never even reach VT status. Dismissing any complaints based on your experience in one very small section of the game will devalue this board as a Verant resource and limits our avenues for affecting change when needed.<br>
<br>
The elitism prevelent on this board to suggest that any mages who don't reach the 'end game' are lazy or undedicated and thus undeserving of consideration is just stupid. The rest of the game does still exist you know, it does still matter. You complained about the problems in Kunark and Velious while dismissing the problems of those below you, and now you praise our role in Luclin while dismissing the same problems you complained about in the past, and worse dismissing the opinions of those who aren't happy with the roles they do have even at your level. Both sides should be expressed, and like I said in the beginning, the initial post was a great testimonial of one mages opinion, without demeaning the opinions of others.<br>
<br>
This would probably be more appropriate in the rant section, but this thread just epitomizes everything that really irritates me about this board. Some of my rant may not apply to what's been said here, but I think it does fit the recent trends on the board, so try ot take it in that context. <p><b>Buppyy O'Boom</b><br>
Jester of Justice<br>
